There’s no place like home for the holidays, but Boston has an extra charm during the holidays with its festive activities! 🎄

Looking for fun & festive things to do in Boston this weekend? Here are a few to check out! ⬇️

❄️ @seaportbos Snowport - Free admission to an adorably decorated market in the Seaport! Stroll, sip & shop your way through this slice of Boston’s North Pole!

🎁 @sowaboston Winter Market - Local vendors galore to finish up your shopping! $10 entry gives you access to vendors, a variety of food and beverages inside or at food trucks + an outdoor fire-pit!

🎄 @liberty_hotel - This historic Boston hotel transforms into a Christmas movie atmosphere! The Liberty is most know at the holidays for its iconic upsidedown Christmas trees hanging from the ceiling. Free admission, but much more fun to view when you book dinner at @clink or hit their bar for a drink!

🛍 @pruboston Holiday Stroll - On Saturday from 2-4pm head to the Pridential Center for a festive day filled with shopping, music & holiday delights! It’s free to stroll and certain vendors will have promos & sales!

☃️ @harvard_square Holiday Fair - Free admission to high energy marketplace! There’s a mix of regional craftspeople and global importers that have a great selection of original, affordable gifts! 

🍻 @ciscobrewers Southie Holiday Stroll - Free admission on Saturday 10am-4pm with @thebroadwaysouthboston, @lincolnsouthbos, @locosouthbos, & @huntersboston! There will be giveaways & costume prizes. Plus, Cisco is donating $1 from every pint to South Boston Neighborhood House, which supports loval families experiencing social & economic stress.

Where are you headed this weekend?! Let me know in the comments & save it to find these ideas later! ⬇️

Jumping on the 2022 season trend! 💯

I could simply say that I’ve had lots of success this year! But that’s not the full truth…

On paper, I ran two world major marathons, started a new job, landed partnerships with some dream brands, and experienced a whole lot of personal growth! 🏅

But truthfully, this has been the hardest year of my life — for reasons I’m not quite ready to share. Instagram is a highlight reel. We show the good times, but this video sprinkles a few glimpses of what life has been like behind the scenes recently.

Here’s what I’ve learned from challenges thrown my way this year:

🤍 Treat everyone with kindness - you never know what they’re going thought 

🤍 Your health matters - so take care of yourself

🤍 True family and friends are everything - tell them you love them and show up for those people in your life

🤍 Check in on your friends - It goes a long way to tell someone you’re thinking about them and remind them you’re here if they need anything

🤍 Give yourself grace - when you’re going through something tough, cut yourself a break

🤍 Stop comparing yourself - Everyone’s journey is different and as soon as you stop comparing, you’ll enjoy life more

Cheers to a healthier and happier 2023! 🥂

Come on a 10-mile tempo run with me! 💯

Excited to be running double digits training for the @bostonmarathon!

A tempo run is a run that has specific milage where you increase your pace significantly, building in speed work to ramp up your endurance! 🏃‍♀️

I ran about an 8:55 pace for regular miles and then 7:23 for the tempo part! 😱

These workouts are challenging, but always very rewarding as they pay dividends in the long run! (Wait I swear I didn’t even mean that pun 😂)

Do you want to see more vlog reels like this?! Let me know in the comments! ⬇️

PS. I was really proud of the first transition and felt like @annaxsitar in a get ready with me video 💁🏼‍♀️

Boston Marathon vlog & recap! 💙💛 

I’m still smiling from finishing 3:24:23! I was nervous bc I had covid 2 weeks prior, but I persevered!

It wasn’t supposed to rain until after I would finish, but it down-poured! It ended up being a blessing I didn’t know this would happen because I didn’t have time to psych myself out & was already committed to breaking 3:30:00. 💪🏼

Miles 1-5:

I actively tried to not make the mistake of going out too fast. I stayed 5-20 secs ahead of my goal pace.

Miles 6-11:

A game changer was @keemonster texted me updates with my official times. I realized I had weaved so much to start that I added on distance. My watch said 7:43/mile for 6 miles, while my official time was 7:54/mile so I had to stop weaving. 

Mile 12-5:

The Wellesley scream tunnel was great! I got a big boost from there & half mark! The course flatten out for a bit & it started to downpour.

Mile 16-20:

I forgot how hard the Newton Hills are! I was on pace to break 3:30 so I dug deep & remembered my why. My shoelace came untied from the rain & I ran 3 miles with it untied. I knew if I stopped before I finished Heartbreak Hill I’d lose my momentum.

Mile 21:

The 💔 was over! IMO the Newtons Hills were harder than Heartbreak. I stopped to tie my shoe. My fingers were numb from the rain & I took a while to retie it. BC is my alma mater tho & the energy kept me going.

Mile 22-25:

This is where the race rly began. I knew I could PR if I gave it my all so I kept my pace.

Mile 26:

The last mile was hard. I slowed down (8:22 vs sub-8 the whole race), even though I felt like I was going faster with my effort. Turning onto Boylston, I was locked in! The crowd got me to the finish line! I was in shock of my PR & BQ, especially with the rain!🏅 My biggest advice is to trust in your training plan & have a race day strategy. Not going out too fast & keeping pace enabled my PR!

A charming 24-hour layover in Lisbon! ✈️🌸

I already have Lisbon on my bucket list to go back to and explore! It was a quick trip, but such we packed so much in! 

My favorite stop we made was on Lisbon’s famous pink street known as Rua Nova do Carvalho! 💕 It’s is the center of Lisbon’s nightlife in the Cais do Sodre neighborhood. IfI’m being honest, maybe just all roads should be pink?! 😂

We found an amazing whole in the wall restaurant called Taverna Sal Grosso (@tabernasalgrosso) and it was one of the best meals I’ve ever had! If you’re traveling, you should definitely stop by and make a reservation when you get there. We didn’t have one, but they squeezed us in for lunch. Their cod dishes were out of this world! 💯

When we were touring it started to rain and we found another hidden gem in a wine shop called Rendezvous. I had a port and tonic, and it’s going to be my new go-to to impress friends at dinner parties. It was unbelievable! 🍷 

We also strolled through some of their beautiful cathedrals including Parish of St. Paul (Pfarrkirche St. Paul)!

Lisbon, I’ll be back for you! 🤍

Did you know that some airlines do up to free 72 hour layovers in Portugal in route to your destination further in Europe! It’s a great way to add an affordable second stop on your trip! 

Let me know in the comments if you’ve heard of this! ⬇️

10 Mile Race vlog & recap! 🏃‍♀️

Finished the annual ‘Blessing of the Fleet’ race with a new PR of 1:15:06!! 🏅 Netting out to 7:31/mile — with 85 degree heat! 😅🥵

I’m really proud of how this race went! I was so nervous because it started at 6pm and it was record high temps, but I still pushed myself and performed well!

Here’s a glance at how it went:

Miles 1-3: These miles were straight up blazing in the sun with no shade in sight for a reprieve. I also was crowd weaving to try to get ahead, so running around people drained me quite a bit. I was also running to every hose in sight to cool off my body temp.

Miles 4-6: An added challenge was the hills during these miles in addition to the sun. I took these miles more conservatively so I could have a little more gas in the tank for the latter miles.

Miles 7-9: These miles had shade coverage and it was so helpful! It gave me more energy and I picked up the pace by about 10 seconds/mile!

Mile 10: Last mile, best mile! ⭐️ I picked up the pace significantly to give it everything I had in the heat — with this mile being at a 6:59 pace! It was hard, but my goal was to finish the last mile the fastest. 

My @corosglobal PACE 2 watch kept me on pace the entire time to I could meet my goals for this race! 💯

I crossed the finish line feeling exhausted, but proud! 🏅

@keemonster and I ran together, and enjoyed the annual race’s fun activities, food trucks, and live music to celebrate our times! 

I’m training for the Beantown Marathon, a local race in September! This was a great race and training run for it! 

Can’t wait for my next 26.2 so soon! 💙💛

Thanks to @mizunorunningusa for my speed Wave Rebellion Flash shoes to help propel me to the finish! 👟

A coastal New England must visit!

Kennebunkport, ME has been on my New England bucket list for a long time, and I’m so happy I finally got to spend some time there!

Here are a few of our trip highlights:

🏘️ Exploring the Charming Town: The streets are so quaint, lined with picturesque shops and historic architecture. Kennebunkport’s charm truly captivated us!

🦞 Clam Shack Delight: We we’re starving when we got in and the infamous Clam Shack did not disappoint! We couldn’t resist the temptation of fresh fried clams and a Maine lobster roll. 

🏃‍♂️ Morning Runs with Coastal Views: A refreshing morning run along the coast was the best way to start the day! You could breathe in the crisp sea air and taking in the breathtaking ocean vistas along with some foliage that was beginning to turn!

🏃‍♂️ Satellite Doughnuts: This boutique donut shop was amazing! The doughnuts were miniature sized so you could order and try a bunch! My favorite was their pop-tart doughnut, with apple cider and double chocolate at close seconds. They were all unreal.

Surprising my grandma, dad, & aunt that I am running the @bostonmarathon with the Alzheimer’s Association in memory of my grandpa, Pop 💜🏃‍♀️

Their reactions are everything! Family means so much to me. While I qualified for the Boston Marathon, I am choosing to fundraise to find a cure for Alzheimer’s because it’s a meaningful cause very close to my heart.

I’ll always cherish the weekends spent with my grandparents growing up. I remember the exact moment I realized something was off with Pop. I was staying with my grandparents for the summer, and when I went off to my internship he asked me where I was going as if I hadn’t done so before. I called my dad and asked him to check in on Pop because I didn’t feel comfortable leaving him alone.

Pop was diagnosed soon after, and for the following decade, my family and I watched Alzheimer’s slowly rob Pop of his memories. With each year that passed, he lost more of himself.

However, Pop always told us to live our lives with ‘love and happiness’ and this was a message that he upheld until the very end. They were two of the last words he could remember as his speech was stolen. Even when he didn’t know who I was anymore, he would ask me if I was happy and if I felt loved. He was an incredibly kind and caring person who taught me how to be the person I am today.

Inspired by his legacy, I am excited to pursue my dream of running with the @alzassociation to fund research for a cure. It’s Giving Tuesday, so please consider donating to my fundraiser! You can donate via the link in my bio or by Venmo-ing @Elizabeth-Pehota.
